<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99237310384631></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99237310384631><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/classes.html?class=12&mid=99237310384631>RE: Help a newbie</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?id=887><span id=Sage>Zuranthium</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>350 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Jun 12th 3:11 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>yes, when someone means training they mean what shows up as "practice" in the game. Specializing is what pure casters can do at level 20. You put your practice points into your specialization fields, and you get better at that area of casting. Specialization lowers the casting cost of spells in that specialized area and also makes you fizzle less. You can train one area of specialization up to 200(evocation for example) and the rest only up to 50. Whichever area hits 51 first is the one that you can take to 200. If you mess up you can do a quest to change your specialization.<br><br>Former Addict of Everquest.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
